  1. List all objects, properties and links that are needed to represent the graph data model

of the knowledge graph of GitHub topics, tags, repositories, and issues.

Objects:

    git: a distributed version control system used for managing software development projects.
    GitHub: a web-based hosting service for version control using git.
    Repository: a location where code is stored and managed.
    Project: a tool for organizing and prioritizing work on a GitHub repository.
    Wiki: a collaborative tool for creating and sharing documentation for a repository.
    Pulse: a visualization of activity for a repository, including issues, pull requests, and code commits.
    Graph: a visualization of the commit history for a repository.
    Code: the source code files in a repository.
    Issue: a problem or feature request that has been identified in a repository.
    Commit: a change to the code that has been made and saved in the repository's history.
    Branch: a parallel version of the code that allows for independent development and testing.
    Clone: a copy of a repository that can be worked on locally.
    Remote: a version of a repository hosted on a remote server.
    Fork: a copy of a repository that can be modified independently of the original.
    Pull: a request to merge changes from one branch or repository to another.
    Log: a history of all commits made to a repository.
    Merge: combining two or more branches or repositories into one.
    Push: uploading local changes to a remote repository.
    Tag: a label assigned to a specific commit to mark it as significant.
    Release: a version of the code that is considered stable and ready for production use.
    History: a record of all changes made to a repository.
    File: a single unit of code or documentation in a repository.
    General Comment : A general comment is a comment that is not associated with any specific line or file in a repository. It can be used to provide feedback, ask questions, or share information about the project.
    Line Comment: A line comment is a comment that is associated with a specific line of code in a file. It can be used to provide feedback, suggest changes, or ask questions about a specific piece of code.
    Review - A review is a process for providing feedback on a pull request or other code change. GitHub provides tools for conducting code reviews, including commenting, approving or rejecting changes, and marking items as resolved.
    User Account: A user account is a personal account that is used to manage and contribute to GitHub repositories. User accounts can be associated with a public profile, and can be used to manage personal repositories or contribute to other projects.
    Organization Account: An organization account is a special type of account that is used to manage repositories and collaborate on projects with other users. Organization accounts can be used to manage team memberships, access control, and other administrative tasks.
    README.md: A README.md file is a special file in a repository that provides documentation and instructions for using the project. It is often the first file that users see when visiting a repository, and can be used to provide context and guidance for the project.
    CONTRIBUTING.md: A CONTRIBUTING.md file is a special file in a repository that provides guidelines and instructions for contributing to the project. It can include information about coding standards, issue reporting, and other aspects of the development process.
    ISSUE_TEMPLATE.md: An ISSUE_TEMPLATE.md file is a special file in a repository that provides a template for creating new issues. It can be used to standardize the issue reporting process and ensure that all necessary information is included in each issue.
    System Configuration: System configuration refers to the configuration of the underlying infrastructure that powers GitHub, including servers, databases, and other systems.
    Global Configuration: Global configuration refers to the configuration of GitHub as a platform, including settings for security, access control, and other platform-wide settings.
    Local Configuration: Local configuration refers to the configuration of a specific repository or development environment, including settings for version control, code review.
Links:



GitHub to Repository

A project can have many repositories.

Repository to Code

A repository can have code.

Repository to Issue

A repository can have issues.

Issue to Repository

An issue belongs to a repository.

Commit to Repository

A commit belongs to a repository.

#Add your code for this requirement in this cell
### List all objects, properties and links that 
###are needed to represent the graph data model of the knowledge graph of StackOverflow tags, questions, and answers.


Object: User
Properties: user_id, display_name, reputation, profile_image_url
Links: asks, answers, follows, edits

Object: Tag
Properties: tag_id, tag_name, description
Links: applied_to, belongs_to, part_of

Object: Question
Properties: question_id, title, body, score, creation_date, view_count, accepted_answer_id
Links: asked_by, tagged_with, has_answer, duplicates, related

Object: Answer
Properties: answer_id, body, score, creation_date, is_accepted
Links: answered_to, commented_on

Object: Comment
Properties: comment_id, body, score, creation_date
Links: commented_on, replied_to

Object: Vote
Properties: vote_id, vote_type, creation_date
Links: voted_on

Object: Badge
Properties: badge_id, badge_name, badge_type, description, creation_date
Links: awarded_to, earns

Object: Review
Properties: review_id, review_type, creation_date, approval_status
Links: reviewed, suggested_edits

Object: Flag
Properties: flag_id, flag_type, creation_date, status
Links: flagged, flagged_by

Object: Close Vote
Properties: vote_id, vote_type, creation_date, status
Links: closed, closed_by, marked_as_duplicate

These objects, properties, and links can be used to represent various aspects of StackOverflow such as 
users, tags, questions, answers, comments, votes, badges, reviews, flags, and close votes.

Links in more detail : 
    A question is tagged with one or more tags.
    An answer is associated with a question it is answering.
    A user can ask many questions and provide many answers.
    A question can have multiple answers.
    A question can be marked as a duplicate of another question.
    A question can be upvoted or downvoted by multiple users.
    An answer can be upvoted or downvoted by multiple users.
    A user can follow a tag and receive updates on related questions.
    A user can flag a question or answer for moderation.
    A question or answer can be edited by multiple users.

### Use networkx package to create the graph data model of the knowledge graph (Network) for GitHub
import networkx as nx

# create an empty mgraph
github_graph = nx.DiGraph()

# add nodes to the graph
github_graph.add_nodes_from([
    'git', 'GitHub', 'Repository', 'Project', 'Wiki', 'Pulse', 'Graph',
    'Code', 'Issue', 'commit', 'branch', 'clone', 'remote', 'fork', 'pull',
    'log', 'merge', 'push', 'status', 'Tag', 'Release', 'history', 'File',
    'General Comment', 'Line Comment', 'Review', 'User Account',
    'Organization Account', 'README.md', 'CONTRIBUTING.md',
    'ISSUE_TEMPLATE.md', 'System Configuration', 'Global Configuration',
    'Local Configuration'
])

# add edges to the graph
github_graph.add_edges_from([
    ('git', 'GitHub', {'name': 'owns'}),
    ('GitHub', 'Repository', {'name': 'owns'}),
    ('GitHub', 'Project', {'name': 'owns'}),
    ('GitHub', 'Wiki', {'name': 'owns'}),
    ('GitHub', 'Pulse', {'name': 'owns'}),
    ('GitHub', 'Graph', {'name': 'owns'}),
    ('Repository', 'Code', {'name': 'has'}),
    ('Repository', 'Issue', {'name': 'has'}),
    ('Repository', 'commit', {'name': 'has'}),
    ('Repository', 'branch', {'name': 'has'}),
    ('Repository', 'Tag', {'name': 'has'}),
    ('Repository', 'Release', {'name': 'has'}),
    ('Repository', 'File', {'name': 'has'}),
    ('Issue', 'General Comment', {'name': 'has'}),
    ('Issue', 'Line Comment', {'name': 'has'}),
    ('Issue', 'Review', {'name': 'has'}),
    ('User Account', 'Repository', {'name': 'owns'}),
    ('User Account', 'Organization Account', {'name': 'member_of'}),
    ('Organization Account', 'Repository', {'name': 'owns'}),
    ('Organization Account', 'Issue', {'name': 'manages'}),
    ('Repository', 'README.md', {'name': 'has'}),
    ('Repository', 'CONTRIBUTING.md', {'name': 'has'}),
    ('Repository', 'ISSUE_TEMPLATE.md', {'name': 'has'}),
    ('Repository', 'System Configuration', {'name': 'has'}),
    ('Repository', 'Global Configuration', {'name': 'has'}),
    ('Repository', 'Local Configuration', {'name': 'has'}),
    ('Repository', 'Tag', {'name': 'tagged_With'}),
    ('Repository', 'Topic', {'name': 'related_to'}),
    ('Repository', 'branch', {'name': 'contains'}),
    ('Repository', 'commit', {'name': 'contains'}),
    ('Project', 'Issue', {'name': 'includes'}),
    ('Project', 'pull', {'name': 'includes'}),
    ('User Account', 'commit', {'name': 'pushed'}),
    ('User Account', 'pull', {'name': 'requested'}),
    ('User Account', 'Issue', {'name': 'reported'}),
    ('User Account', 'Review', {'name': 'reviewed'}),
    ('User Account', 'File', {'name': 'uploaded'}),
    ('User Account', 'fork', {'name': 'forked'}),
    ('User Account', 'Repository', {'name': 'collaborates_on'}),
    ('User Account', 'Issue', {'name': 'commented_on'}),
    ('User Account', 'commit', {'name': 'authored'}),
    ('User Account', 'commit', {'name': 'committed'}),
    ('User Account', 'branch', {'name': 'created'}),
    ('User Account', 'Tag', {'name': 'created'}),
    ('User Account', 'Release', {'name': 'created'}),
    ('Readme.md', 'Repository', {'name': 'contains info'}),
    ('Review', 'pull', {'name': 'evaluates'}),
    ('Review', 'push', {'name': 'evaluates'})
    
])

# add the properties as attributes to the nodes and edges
github_graph.nodes['User Account']['properties'] = ['username', 'email', 'location', 'website']
github_graph.nodes['Repository']['properties'] = ['name', 'description', 'language', 'created_at', 'updated_at']
github_graph.nodes['Organization Account']['properties'] = ['name', 'description', 'location', 'website']
github_graph.nodes['pull']['properties'] = ['title', 'description', 'created_at', 'updated_at']
github_graph.nodes['Issue']['properties'] = ['title', 'description', 'created_at', 'updated_at']
github_graph.nodes['commit']['properties'] = ['message', 'created_at']
github_graph.nodes['Tag']['properties'] = ['created_at']
github_graph.nodes['Topic']['properties'] = ['name']

#Draw the graph
pos = nx.spring_layout(github_graph)
nx.draw_networkx_nodes(github_graph, pos, node_color = 'blue', node_size = 200)
nx.draw_networkx_edges(github_graph, pos, edge_color = 'green')
edge_labels = nx.get_edge_attributes(github_graph, 'name')
nx.draw_networkx_edge_labels(github_graph, pos, edge_labels=edge_labels, font_size = 4, font_color = 'purple')
nx.draw_networkx_labels(github_graph, pos, font_size = 8, font_family = 'Arial')
plt.axis('off')
plt.show()

print("Nodes of Github graph:")
print(github_graph.nodes())
print("\nEdges of Github graph:")
print(github_graph.edges())

print("\n\nOutput all the properties and links of the nodes and edges in the graph:\n\n")
for node in github_graph.nodes:
    node_properties = github_graph.nodes[node].get('properties')
    if node_properties:
        print(f"{node} node properties: {node_properties}")

print("\n\n")
for edge in github_graph.edges:
    edge_properties = github_graph.edges[edge].get('name')
    if edge_properties:
        print(f"{edge[0]} to {edge[1]} edge link: {edge_properties}")

### Use networkx package to create the graph data model of the knowledge graph (Network) for StackOverflow
import networkx as nx
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Empty graph creation
stackoverflow_graph = nx.DiGraph()

# Add nodes 
stackoverflow_graph.add_nodes_from(['User', 'Tags', 'Questions', 'Answers', 'Comment', 'Badge', 'Vote', 'Review','Flag'])

# Add edges with properties
stackoverflow_graph.add_edges_from([
    ('User', 'Questions', {'type': 'ask'}),
    ('User', 'Answers', {'type': 'answer'}),
    ('User', 'Comment', {'type': 'comment'}),
    ('User', 'Vote', {'type': 'vote'}),
    ('Questions', 'Tags', {'type': 'tagged with'}),
    ('Questions', 'Answers', {'type': 'has answer'}),
    ('Answers', 'Vote', {'type': 'vote'}),
    ('Questions', 'Comment', {'type': 'has comment'}),
    ('Answers', 'Comment', {'type': 'has comment'}),
    ('Comment', 'Comment', {'type': 'reply to'}),
    ('User', 'Badge', {'type': 'earned'}),
    ('User', 'Review', {'type': 'reviewed'}),
    ('User', 'Flag', {'type': 'flagged'}),
    ('Flag', 'User', {'type': 'flagged_by'})
])


# Define node properties
stackoverflow_graph.nodes['User']['properties'] = ['User_id', 'Display_Name','Reputation', 'CreationDate', 'Location']
stackoverflow_graph.nodes['Tags']['properties'] = ['Tag_id', 'Description','Name']
stackoverflow_graph.nodes['Questions']['properties'] = ['Question_id','Title', 'CreationDate', 'Score','Body', 'View_count','Accepted_answer_id']
stackoverflow_graph.nodes['Answers']['properties'] = ['Answer_id','CreationDate', 'Score','Body','is_accpeted']
stackoverflow_graph.nodes['Comment']['properties'] = ['Comment_id','CreationDate', 'Body','Score']
stackoverflow_graph.nodes['Badge']['properties'] = ['Badge_id''Name', 'CreationDate', 'Description']
stackoverflow_graph.nodes['Vote']['properties'] = ['Vote_type_id', 'CreationDate']
stackoverflow_graph.nodes['Review']['properties'] = ['CreationDate', 'ReviewTaskId','Approval_status']



# Draw the graph
pos = nx.spring_layout(stackoverflow_graph)
nx.draw_networkx_nodes(stackoverflow_graph, pos, node_color='blue', node_size=400)
nx.draw_networkx_edges(stackoverflow_graph, pos, edge_color='green')
edge_labels = nx.get_edge_attributes(stackoverflow_graph, 'type')
nx.draw_networkx_edge_labels(stackoverflow_graph, pos, edge_labels=edge_labels, font_size=7, font_color='purple')
nx.draw_networkx_labels(stackoverflow_graph, pos, font_size=10, font_family='Arial')
plt.axis('off')
plt.show()

# Print node properties
for node in stackoverflow_graph.nodes():
    print(f'{node} properties: {stackoverflow_graph.nodes[node]}')

# Print edge properties
for edge in stackoverflow_graph.edges():
    print(f'{edge} properties: {stackoverflow_graph.edges[edge]}')

### Use networkx package to create the graph data model of the knowledge graph (Network) for the combined data,
###we will call it the the BugHub knowledge graph, of GitHub and StackOverflow

import networkx as nx
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# empty graph creation
BugHub = nx.Graph()

# Adding nodes
nodes = ['User', 'Repository', 'Issue', 'Tag', 'Question', 'Answer', 'Comment', 'Badge', 'Vote', 'Review']
BugHub.add_nodes_from(nodes)

# Adding edges
edges = [('User', 'Repository', {'type': 'own'}),
         ('User', 'Issue', {'type': 'created, assigned to'}),
         ('User', 'Commit', {'type': 'does'}),
         ('User', 'Pulls', {'type': 'creates'}),
         ('User', 'Comment', {'type': 'posted on'}),
         ('User', 'Badge', {'type': 'earned'}),
         ('User', 'Vote', {'type': 'cast'}),
         ('User', 'Review', {'type': 'submitted'}),
         ('User', 'Question', {'type': 'asked, voted'}),
         ('User', 'Answer', {'type': 'answered, voted'}),

         ('Repository', 'Issue', {'type': 'has'}),
         ('Repository', 'Tag', {'type': 'tagged with'}),
         ('Repository', 'User', {'type': 'owned by'}),

         ('Issue', 'Comment', {'type': 'has'}),
         ('Issue', 'Label', {'type': 'has'}),
         ('Issue', 'User', {'type': 'created by, assigned to'}),
         ('Issue', 'Milestone', {'type': 'has'}),
         ('Issue', 'PullRequest', {'type': 'associated with'}),
         ('Issue', 'Project', {'type': 'associated with'}),
         ('Issue', 'Repository', {'type': 'reported on'}),

         ('Tag', 'Repository', {'type': 'has'}),
         ('Tag', 'Issue', {'type': 'tagged with'}),
         ('Tag', 'Question', {'type': 'tagged with'}),

         ('Question', 'Answer', {'type': 'has one or more'}),
         ('Question', 'User', {'type': 'asked by, voted by'}),
         ('Question', 'Tag', {'type': 'tagged with'}),

         ('Answer', 'Question', {'type': 'answered to, voted by'}),
         ('Answer', 'User', {'type': 'answered by, voted by'}),

         ('Comment', 'Issue', {'type': 'posted on'}),
         ('Comment', 'Question', {'type': 'posted on'}),
         ('Comment', 'Answer', {'type': 'posted on'}),
         ('Comment', 'User', {'type': 'posted by'}),

         ('Badge', 'User', {'type': 'earned by'}),

         ('Vote', 'Question', {'type': 'cast on'}),
         ('Vote', 'Answer', {'type': 'cast on'}),
         ('Vote', 'Comment', {'type': 'cast on'}),

         ('Review', 'User', {'type': 'submitted by'}),
         ('Review', 'Repository', {'type': 'reviewed for'})]

BugHub.add_edges_from(edges)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 10))
pos = nx.spring_layout(BugHub)
nx.draw_networkx_nodes(BugHub, pos, node_color='blue', node_size=400)
nx.draw_networkx_edges(BugHub, pos, edge_color='gray')
edge_labels = nx.get_edge_attributes(BugHub, 'type')
nx.draw_networkx_edge_labels(BugHub, pos, edge_labels=edge_labels, font_size=7, font_color='purple')
nx.draw_networkx_labels(BugHub, pos, font_size=10, font_family='Arial')
plt.axis('off')
plt.show()

# Print edge properties
for edge in BugHub.edges():
    print(f'{edge} properties: {BugHub.edges[edge]}')

import networkx as nx
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import requests

# Initialize the graph
graph = nx.Graph()

# Set up authentication using a personal access token
token = "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"
headers = {"Authorization": f"Bearer {token}"}

# Define the GitHub API endpoint for retrieving repository information
GITHUB_API_URL = "https://api.github.com/repos/"

# Define the StackOverflow API endpoint for retrieving question information
STACKOVERFLOW_API_URL = "https://api.stackexchange.com/2.3/questions"
stackoverflow_key = "irAprM2zS4dk0AC8TDnGGQ(("
stackoverflow_headers = {"X-API-Key": stackoverflow_key}

# Create a dictionary of repositories and their associated StackOverflow tags
repos = {
    "React": {
        "github": "facebook/react",
        "stackoverflow_tag": "reactjs"
    },
    "Angular": {
        "github": "angular/angular",
        "stackoverflow_tag": "angular"
    },
    "Visualization": {
        "github": "d3/d3",
        "stackoverflow_tag": "d3.js"
    }
}

# Go through the repositories and fetch their details
for repo_name, repo_info in repos.items():
    
    # Get information about a GitHub repository using the GitHub API
    github_url = GITHUB_API_URL + repo_info["github"]
    github_response = requests.get(github_url, headers=headers)

    if github_response.ok:
        print(f"Retrieved repository information for {repo_name} from GitHub API.")
    else:
        print(f"Failed to retrieve repository information for {repo_name} from GitHub API.")

    github_data = github_response.json()

    # Get the topics associated with a GitHub repository using the GitHub API
    topics_url = github_url + "/topics"
    topics_response = requests.get(topics_url, headers=headers)
    topics_data = topics_response.json()

    # Get the number of issues associated with a repository from the GitHub API
    issues_params = {"state": "open", "type": "issue"}
    issues_url = github_url + "/issues"
    issues_response = requests.get(issues_url, headers=headers, params=issues_params)
    issues_data = issues_response.json()

    open_issues_count = github_data["open_issues_count"]
    stars = github_data['stargazers_count']
    forks = github_data['forks_count']
    watchers = github_data['subscribers_count']
    
    # Get the number of tags associated with a repository from the GitHub API, 
    # using pagination to retrieve more tags if necessary
    tag_url = github_url + "/tags"
    tag_count = 0
    while tag_url:
        tag_response = requests.get(tag_url, headers=headers)
        tag_data = tag_response.json()
        for tag in tag_data:
            tag_count += 1
        tag_url = tag_response.links.get('next', {}).get('url')
    graph = nx.Graph()
    # Add the github node to the graph
    graph.add_node(repo_name, properties="repository")
    graph.add_node(open_issues_count, properties="issues")
    graph.add_node(stars, properties="stars")
    graph.add_node(forks, properties="forks")
    graph.add_node(watchers, properties="watchers")

    
    # Create an edge between the nodes
    graph.add_edge(repo_name, open_issues_count, type="has open issue count")
    graph.add_edge(repo_name, stars, type="has stars")
    graph.add_edge(repo_name, forks, type="has forks")
    graph.add_edge(repo_name, watchers, type="has watchers")
    
    
    # Retrieve questions related to the repository from StackOverflow API
    stackoverflow_params = {
        "order": "desc",
        "sort": "votes",
        "tagged": repo_info["stackoverflow_tag"],
        "site": "stackoverflow",
        "pagesize": 25
    }
    stackoverflow_response = requests.get(STACKOVERFLOW_API_URL, headers=stackoverflow_headers, params=stackoverflow_params)
    stackoverflow_data = stackoverflow_response.json()
    
    for item in stackoverflow_data["items"]:
        user = item['owner']['display_name']
        question = item['title']
        tags = item['tags']
        answer_count = item['answer_count']
    
    #Add the github node to the graph
    graph.add_node(user, properties="user")
    graph.add_node(question, properties="question")
    graph.add_node(answer_count, properties="answer count")


    # Create an edge between the nodes
    graph.add_edge(repo_name, user, type="owns")
    graph.add_edge(user, question, type="asks, answers")
    graph.add_edge(question, answer_count, type="has answer count")
    
    
#Draw the graph
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(25, 25))
pos = nx.spring_layout(graph)
nx.draw_networkx_nodes(graph, pos, node_color = 'blue', node_size = 750)
nx.draw_networkx_edges(graph, pos, edge_color = 'green')
edge_labels = nx.get_edge_attributes(graph, 'type')
nx.draw_networkx_edge_labels(graph, pos, edge_labels=edge_labels, font_size = 11, font_color = 'purple')
nx.draw_networkx_labels(graph, pos, font_size = 11, font_family = 'Arial')
plt.axis('off')
plt.show()

### Store your GitHub data in a DataFrame 
### and retrieve from the DataFrame the repo that has the highest number of GitHub issues created.

from datetime import datetime, timedelta
from github import Github
import pandas as pd

#GitHub API authentication token
TOKEN = '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'

#Instantiate Github object
gh = Github(TOKEN)

#List of repositories to retrieve data for
repositories = [
'angular/angular',
'angular/material',
'angular/angular-cli',
'SebastianM/angular-google-maps',
'd3/d3',
'facebook/react',
'tensorflow/tensorflow',
'keras-team/keras',
'pallets/flask'
]

#Date range for filtering data
today = datetime.today()
two_years_ago = today - timedelta(days=730) #365 * 2

#Collect data about each repository and store it in a DataFrame
repo_data = []
for repository in repositories:
    repo = gh.get_repo(repository)
    repo_dict = {
    'Name': repo.name,
    'Description': repo.description,
    'Stars': repo.stargazers_count,
    'Forks': repo.forks_count,
    'Watchers': repo.watchers_count,
    'Open Issues': repo.open_issues_count,
    'Last Updated': repo.updated_at,
    'Number of Commits (past 2 years)': repo.get_commits(since=two_years_ago).totalCount
    }
    repo_data.append(repo_dict)
    df = pd.DataFrame(repo_data)

#Change the data type of the 'Open Issues' column from string to integer
df['Open Issues'] = df['Open Issues'].astype(int)

#Find the repository with the highest number of open issues
max_open_issues_repo = df.loc[df['Open Issues'].idxmax(), 'Name']
print(f"The repository with the highest number of open issues is {max_open_issues_repo}.")

The repository with the highest number of open issues is tensorflow.

### Store your StackOverflow data in a DataFrame and retrieve 
###from the DataFrame the repo/tag that has the highest number of StackOverflow questions created. 


import pandas as pd
import requests
import time
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')

# Define the repositories and their associated tags
repositories = [
    ("angular/angular", "angular"),
    ("angular/material", "angular-material"),
    ("angular/angular-cli", "angular-cli"),
    ("SebastianM/angular-google-maps", "angular-google-maps"),
    ("d3/d3", "d3.js"),
    ("facebook/react", "reactjs"),
    ("tensorflow/tensorflow", "tensorflow"),
    ("keras-team/keras", "keras"),
    ("pallets/flask", "flask")
]

# Define the StackOverflow API endpoint and key
api_url = "https://api.stackexchange.com/2.3/questions"
api_key = "irAprM2zS4dk0AC8TDnGGQ(("

# Define the query parameters
params = {
    "order": "desc",
    "sort": "votes",
    "site": "stackoverflow",
    "pagesize": 1,
    "key": api_key
}

# Create an empty DataFrame to store the data
df = pd.DataFrame(columns=["Repository", "Tag", "Questions"])

# Loop through the repositories and retrieve information on their associated tags
for repository, tag in repositories:
    # Define the query parameters
    params["tagged"] = tag
    
    # Date range for filtering data
    today = datetime.today()
    two_years_ago = today - timedelta(days=730) #365 * 2

    # Set the date range for the query
    date_string = two_years_ago.strftime("%Y-%m-%d")
    unix_timestamp = int(time.mktime(time.strptime(date_string, "%Y-%m-%d")))
    params["fromdate"] = unix_timestamp

    # Make the API request
    response = requests.get(api_url, params=params)

    # Parse the response
    data = response.json()
    
    # Extract the number of questions
    num_questions = data["items"][0]["question_id"]
    
    # Add the data to the DataFrame
    df = df.append({"Repository": repository, "Tag": tag, "Questions": num_questions}, ignore_index=True)

# Change the data type of the 'Questions' column from string to integer
df["Questions"] = df["Questions"].astype(int)

# Get the row with the highest number of questions
max_questions_row = df.loc[df["Questions"].idxmax()]

# Print the repository/tag with the highest number of questions
print(f"The repository/tag with the highest number of questions is {max_questions_row['Repository']}/{max_questions_row['Tag']} with {max_questions_row['Questions']} questions.")

The repository/tag with the highest number of questions is angular/angular-cli/angular-cli with 73156911 questions.

    "order": "desc",
    "sort": "votes",
    "site": "stackoverflow",
    "pagesize": 5,
